  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Lambda\n=\n\\frac{\\mathbf{B}^2}\n{\\rho\\,\\mu\\,\\Omega^2}.\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nLet $\\mathbf{B}$ be magnetic field strength, $\\rho$ mass density, $\\mu$ magnetic permeability, and $\\Omega$ angular rotation rate.\n\nThe magnetic contribution is represented by field magnitude squared:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\mathbf{B}^2 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe inertial-rotational scale is represented by:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\rho\\,\\mu\\,\\Omega^2 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe dimensionless comparison between these two effects defines the Elsasser-type parameter:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\Lambda\n=\n\\frac{\\mathbf{B}^2}\n{\\rho\\,\\mu\\,\\Omega^2}.\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe attractor condition is:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\Lambda \\approx 1 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nThe Elsasser attractor occurs when magnetic and rotational scales enter near-balance, producing a self-organizing critical manifold.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
